---
description: Use enums for closed string sets in TypeScript (not raw literals)
alwaysApply: true
---

# Closed sets use enums (TypeScript)

When a value is drawn from a **fixed, known set** of strings (API enums, device
families/kinds, layout modes, rule triggers, settings tabs, credential sources,
toast variants), define a **string enum** (or a const-object enum — see below)
in `web/src/` (typically next to the domain types in `types.ts` or a small
`*-enums.ts` module) and compare against enum members — not bare string
literals.

```ts
// Good
enum DeviceKind {
  Door = "door",
  Occupancy = "occupancy",
  Speaker = "speaker",
  Switch = "switch",
}

if (device.kind === DeviceKind.Occupancy) {
  ...
}

// Avoid in application code
if (device.kind === "occupancy") {
  ...
}
```

Wire / JSON values stay the same (`"occupancy"`, etc.). Prefer **string enums**
whose members equal the API wire value so `JSON` and FastAPI payloads need no
mapping layer.

This mirrors Python’s `StrEnum` rule (`.cursor/rules/python-closed-set-enums.mdc`).

## Const-object alternative (when `enum` is awkward)

If a bundler or `erasableSyntaxOnly`-style constraint makes `enum` undesirable,
use a const object + derived type (same call-site discipline):

```ts
export const DeviceKind = {
  Door: "door",
  Occupancy: "occupancy",
  Speaker: "speaker",
  Switch: "switch",
} as const;
export type DeviceKind = (typeof DeviceKind)[keyof typeof DeviceKind];

if (device.kind === DeviceKind.Occupancy) {
  ...
}
```

Do **not** treat a bare string union alone as sufficient when comparisons still
hard-code `"occupancy"` at call sites — the named members are the point.

## Exceptions

- One-off **user-facing copy** (button labels, toast prose) — those stay string
  constants / message modules (`test-assert-message-constants.mdc` when asserted
  in tests).
- **DOM / CSS / third-party** literals required for interoperability (`"click"`,
  Leaflet options, `data-*` attribute names).
- **Test fixture JSON** that must match wire payloads may keep string literals;
  prefer importing enum members when asserting application branches.
